6. WHAT EACH MAJOR PART OF THE REPOSITORY EXISTS FOR
==================================================

This section explains the repository folder by folder.


6.1 `admin/` - the operator desktop app

This is a desktop control console built for the people who prepare and maintain Hivemind.

Its visible pages are:

- `Dashboard`: local stack status and local start/stop controls.
- `Theory Frameworks`: knowledge base creation, theory document uploads, pasted framework text, smart upload, and retrieval testing.
- `Simulations`: standalone simulation creation, editing, testing, and a separate workflow for uploading a Python simulation plus its description.
- `Practicality Units`: creation and publishing of practicality-side agents, attachment of knowledge, upload of practicality documents, prompt preview, and testing.
- `Settings`: server connection settings and API key management.

Important nontechnical takeaway:

- the Admin app is how the company shapes what Hivemind knows and how it judges things;
- it is not the main end-user question screen.

Important nuance:

- this app still contains a local all-in-one mode where it can start PostgreSQL, Qdrant, and the cloud server on the same machine;
- at the same time, the newer documentation emphasizes a hosted AWS server;
- so the codebase clearly carries both a hosted-cloud story and a local-bundled story.


6.2 `client/` - the real end-user desktop app

This is the actual user-facing analysis application.

It currently provides:

- username-based login,
- server connectivity checking,
- optional server URL override,
- a single-screen analysis workspace,
- sliders and advanced controls,
- optional manual agent selection,
- optional use-case and decision-type selection,
- live streamed progress during the run,
- result viewing,
- audit trail viewing,
- and text export.

Important nontechnical takeaway:

- the client is focused and narrow by design;
- it is meant to submit one problem at a time and show one run's results clearly.

It does not currently look like a broad account portal or reporting dashboard.


6.3 `client-demo/` - a presentation demo

This is a demonstration-only version of the client.

It appears designed to explain the concept visually rather than to perform real live analyses.

It includes:

- a built-in business case,
- fake accessible data files,
- a scripted veto-and-restart story,
- a scripted final report,
- and a "pause/resume" demo behavior.

Important nontechnical takeaway:

- this folder is for showing the product story;
- it is not the production analysis app.


6.4 `cloud/` - the central server and analysis brain

This is the most important product folder in the repository.

It contains the server that:

- receives requests from the Admin and Client apps,
- stores agents, knowledge, simulations, clients, and analysis results,
- processes uploaded documents,
- performs search over stored knowledge,
- calls the AI model,
- runs the theory/practicality debate process,
- and serves lightweight web dashboards for operations and knowledge browsing.

Inside `cloud/`, there are several distinct roles:

`cloud/app/`
- the web server and API layer.
- This is where the routes live: login, agents, knowledge bases, simulations, settings, analyses, health checks, clients, client data, and scraped sources.

`cloud/hivemind_core/`
- the reusable "analysis engine."
- This is the pure logic of the Hivemind debate workflow: theory generation, critique, revision, aggregation, practicality scoring, veto, and final output.

`cloud/app/models/`
- definitions of the kinds of records the system stores.

`cloud/app/rag/`
- the document-processing and document-search machinery.
- This is what extracts text, chunks it, embeds it, and pushes it into the vector search system.

`cloud/app/services/`
- support services such as document optimization, file storage, and simulation execution.

`cloud/app/templates/`
- simple browser pages for server health and a browsable knowledge browser.

`cloud/scripts/`
- server startup and maintenance scripts.

`cloud/tests/`
- a small automated test area, mainly around simulations, helper logic, and core data types.


6.5 `deploy/aws/` - production hosting files

This folder exists to run the backend in the cloud.

In simple terms, it defines how to host:

- the Hivemind app server,
- the vector database,
- a PostgreSQL database,
- and optional file storage in S3.

The AWS deployment story in this repo is:

- EC2 runs the app and Qdrant,
- RDS hosts PostgreSQL,
- S3 can hold uploaded files,
- Docker Compose ties the pieces together on the server,
- bootstrap and deploy scripts help bring the stack up.

Important nontechnical takeaway:

- this folder is about how the product is hosted, not how users interact with it.


